{"id": "30140", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30140", "title": "Scroll of Reversal", "text": "The &lt;a href=\"Scroll%20of%20Reversal\"&gt;Scroll of Reversal&lt;/a&gt; is a quest item used during &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%209\"&gt;Chapter 9&lt;/a&gt; of . It can be acquired from &lt;a href=\"Iycanth%20the%20Mad\"&gt;Iycanth the Mad&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Abazigal%27s%20Lair%20Iycanth%20the%20Mad%20Bondari\"&gt;4th Area&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Abazigal%27s%20Lair\"&gt;Abazigal's Lair&lt;/a&gt;, either by completing his quest for the &lt;a href=\"Gauth%20Eyestalk\"&gt;Gauth Eyestalk&lt;/a&gt; or by killing him. The scroll can then be used on the green dragon &lt;a href=\"Fll%27Yissetat\"&gt;Fll'Yissetat&lt;/a&gt;, who will provide &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href=\"Abazigal%27s%20Wardstone\"&gt;Abazigal's Wardstone&lt;/a&gt; and give them access to &lt;a href=\"Abazigal%27s%20Hideout\"&gt;Abazigal's Hideout&lt;/a&gt; without a fight."}
{"id": "32459", "revid": "50866439", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32459", "title": "Scrolls", "text": "Scrolls are items which either contain written information, or have magical functions. In the latter case, they are commonly called \"spell scrolls\" and are used for the purpose of casting magic. In Baldur's Gate and Baldur's Gate II, spell scrolls have restrictions on what classes can use them. \nScrolls.\nRegular scrolls, typically called \"scrolls,\" have no magic function and often carry valuable bits of written information that pertain to characters or the world setting. Letters also fall under the scroll item type. Some scrolls can be very important and advance the central plotline or may be required to progress in some quests.\nSpell Scrolls.\nSpell scrolls are a type of item used for the casting of magic, and have 2 main functions. First, by right-clicking they can be written (scribed) into a character's spellbook, where inscription has a chance of success based upon the character's &lt;a href=\"intelligence\"&gt;intelligence&lt;/a&gt; and/or specialist school. Second, spell scrolls can be a limited-use item to cast a spell directly, without needing to have the spell prepared or scribed. \u00a0\nThe 3 magic categories of spell scrolls are arcane, divine, and protection. These correspond to the spell type on the scroll. eg Wizard spells are arcane, Cleric spells are divine, and non-type protection spells are protection. Note: since divine spells are innately learned, divine spell scrolls are less common than the others. Notably in , there are no divine spell scrolls, instead various temples offer to perform divine spells for gold. In divine scrolls are found only in Durlag's Tower. \u00a0\nGameplay/mechanics.\nIdentification.\nTo quickly ID which magic category (arcane, divine, protection) a spell scroll belongs, there are signs to reference. Arcane scrolls list the magic school in parenthesis below the name. Protection scrolls have a green icon. Divine scrolls have a blue icon. \nScribing.\nScribing a scroll simply means writing it successfully to the spellbook. (The actual rules for \"casting\" spells from memory are covered in [link]). To do this right-click on the scroll and select 'write.' If a caster hasn't scribed a spell but has the ability to do so, that scroll will be highlighted green. As mentioned previously, writing a scroll to a character's spellbook is not guaranteed to be successful; the rate of success depends upon the caster's &lt;a href=\"intelligence\"&gt;intelligence&lt;/a&gt; score and/or specialist school. Specialist mages get a 15% bonus in writing spells from their specialization school, but a 15% penalty for all schools outside it. \nOnce a spell has been scribed, a scroll is no longer needed to cast the spell, however it still must be memorized and then only has a limited number of uses per rest (depending on the caster's level). \nAs a limited-use item.\nAs a broad 'rule of thumb', the rules for using scrolls are: arcane scrolls can be used by arcane casters, divine scrolls by divine casters, and green protection scrolls by nearly everyone with INT 9 (except for Wizard Slayers). There are, however, some exceptions based on class. For a definite list of spell scroll usage by class, refer to the table below. Note that casting via scrolls doesn't have the same restrictions as casting from memory, and although some information on the wiki pages may appear inconsistent with the rules, this table was vetted by a top wiki contributor. \nSpell scrolls can be used before the caster reaches the XP level required to cast the spell from memory. For example, a level 1 mage can cast the level 5 &lt;a href=\"Cloudkill\"&gt;Cloudkill&lt;/a&gt; spell if they have the scroll in inventory. This makes spell scrolls very powerful in certain scenarios. (One example would be if playing solo as a dual-class Level 2 M&gt;F, the character can cast high level mage spells from scrolls whilst gaining high levels in the fighter class). "}
{"id": "13571", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13571", "title": "Scrooloose", "text": "Scrooloose is a lawful &lt;a href=\"lawful%20neutral\"&gt;neutral&lt;/a&gt; / &lt;a href=\"lawful%20evil\"&gt;evil&lt;/a&gt; character in \"\". He appears on the roof of the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt; with former friends of &lt;a href=\"Korgan\"&gt;Korgan&lt;/a&gt; during his &lt;a href=\"Help%20Korgan%20Recover%20the%20Book%20of%20Kaza\"&gt;companion quest&lt;/a&gt;. Scrooloose can backstab (although only at X2 modifier) even while visible. "}
{"id": "5911", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5911", "title": "Sea's Bounty Tavern", "text": "Sea's Bounty Tavern is an inn and tavern in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Docks%20District\"&gt;Docks District&lt;/a&gt; during \"\".Its proprietor &lt;a href=\"The%20Thumb\"&gt;The Thumb&lt;/a&gt; has rooms to let and sells drinks. &lt;a href=\"Gracie\"&gt;Gracie&lt;/a&gt; is the bar wench. If you talk to her, she will tell you a little bit about the owner of the tavern. If &lt;a href=\"Edwin%20Odesseiron\"&gt;Edwin&lt;/a&gt; is in the party, she'll have a LOT more to say!\nDon't forget to try some different Drinks at the bar. Sure you'll get &lt;a href=\"Intoxicated\"&gt;Intoxicated&lt;/a&gt; if you drink too many, but the rumors and immersion of various tidbits, scuttlebutt and chit chat is worth it. This IS the world of Baldur's Gate, with some extra content for those willing to quaff a few. So, spend a few golden shillings, get your buzz going, and hear the latest buzz as well. The more expensive the beverage, the better the rumor. Many rumors are actually factual.\nSpeak with the noblemen and noblewomen on the first and second floors. Also try listening in to the sea shanty sung by the sailor patron. It is a classic Baldur's Gate style gem, that may make you laugh. You'll be singing it to yourself, long after leaving the Tavern.\nLayout.\nThe establishment has two floors, the first floor for drinking and socializing, and the top floor for dining and lodgers. There is a secret connection to the &lt;a href=\"Sea%27s%20Bounty%20Tavern%20%28Pirates%27%20Hideout%29\"&gt;Pirate Hideout in a hidden cave&lt;/a&gt; if you can find it.\nContainers.\nThe first floor has three containers, the table is empty.\nThe second floor only has one container.\nBaron Ployer and Jaheira.\nIf &lt;a href=\"Jaheira\"&gt;Jaheira&lt;/a&gt; is in your party, a man named &lt;a href=\"Baron%20Ployer\"&gt;Baron Ployer&lt;/a&gt; will be in the tavern the first time you visit. He has a grudge against Jaheira, and will summon a couple of mages to cast a curse on her. This starts the &lt;a href=\"Save%20Jaheira%20from%20Baron%20Ployer%27s%20Curse\"&gt;Save Jaheira from Baron Ployer's Curse&lt;/a&gt; quest.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes a few revisions to creatures that may fight back, such Baron Ployer, Officer Dirth, or the Pirate Captain for example. See those individual pages for information."}
{"id": "50596", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50596", "title": "Sea's Bounty Tavern (Pirates' Hideout)", "text": "Sea's Bounty Tavern (Pirates' Hideout) is a hidden cave hollow behind the Tavern, within the hillside overlooking the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Athkatla Docks&lt;/a&gt; area. There is a large pool of brackish water in the cave as well. Torches and oil lamps shed some illumination in the dank interior, and a brazier with coals glows against one wall with a pot of some simmering gruel upon it. Various crates, barrels and cargo netting are piled about the cavern walls. \nA Pirate Captain and some of some of his current crew are inside the hideout. Apparently, they have paid a fee to &lt;a href=\"The%20Thumb\"&gt;The Thumb&lt;/a&gt; for the purpose of having a secret and secure cave to conduct business, stash contraband and hide from authorities. When you move aside the secret wall panel in the tavern and descend a few rock-hewn steps, you are immediately addressed by the Captain, who is not pleased with your uninvited disturbance.\nYou will face the &lt;a href=\"Pirate%20Captain\"&gt;Pirate Captain&lt;/a&gt;, Three &lt;a href=\"Pirate%20%28Hideout%29\"&gt;Pirate Crew&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Pirate%20%28Hideout%29\"&gt;Pirate Mage&lt;/a&gt;. They are fond of hurling missiles from a distance and then engaging in melee when in close quarters. The Captain is a skilled swordsman, and crossed blades many times before. The Mage will try and assist in your demise by way of arcane energies but poses no physical threat.\nShould you triumph, then after combat, their booty can be claimed from the pool, including , a &lt;a href=\"Pearl%20Necklace\"&gt;Pearl Necklace&lt;/a&gt; and two &lt;a href=\"Pearl\"&gt;Pearl&lt;/a&gt;s. Some other equipment can be found on the recently deceased. No one will know about any of this, as \"Dead Men Tell No Tales\", and Thumb will be trying to keep this episode a secret as well. Could be bad for his cave rental business if the word got out.\nMod content.\nAs is standard for the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod, the creatures are revised by SCS AI scripts to enhance their tactical intelligence and combat behavior. With the \"Smarter Mages\" component, the spell casting pirate has a &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Sequencer\"&gt;Minor Sequencer&lt;/a&gt; prepared, and when hostilities ensue the mage will initiate a contingency that launches several protective spells upon himself. Then offensive spells will be cast at you, the intruder, as long as the mage is not disrupted and able to do so. Note that the Pirate Captain is a skilled swordsman, and can dish out and hit frequently with his enchanted blade. See the individual creature page for more information. See also the screenshot above showing the combat text and initial spell casts in a SCS and &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; modded game in BG2EE 2.6."}
