{"id": "24755", "revid": "50459896", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24755", "title": "Sea Troll", "text": "The Sea Troll is a marine breed of trolls that has developed gills in order to hunt in salt water.\nIts scales are olive-blue in color. Despite being the same size as the ordinary &lt;a href=\"troll\"&gt;troll&lt;/a&gt; (9 feet), a saltwater troll's forelimbs are shorter and weaker than those of an ordinary troll, but it has developed a huge maw and numerous fangs.\nLike most other trolls it regenerates, and once brought to an unconscious state (with a minimum of 1 hit point), it becomes impervious to everything but &lt;a href=\"Acid%20damage\"&gt;acid&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"fire%20damage\"&gt;fire damage&lt;/a&gt;. If it is not quickly slain, it regains its health and rises up to fight again."}
{"id": "35554", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35554", "title": "Sea Zombie", "text": "Sea Zombies are a variant of &lt;a href=\"zombies\"&gt;zombies&lt;/a&gt; created by animating either the corpse of somebody who died by drowning or a corpse that has spent a prolonged period of time in water. Their primary difference from normal zombies is their ability to swim extremely well in water. They are most likely to be created by &lt;a href=\"necromancer\"&gt;necromancer&lt;/a&gt;s of the aquatic races, such as &lt;a href=\"sahuagin\"&gt;sahuagin&lt;/a&gt;.\nAppendix.\nBackground.\nSea zombies (also known as drowned ones) are the animated corpses of humans who died at sea. Although similar to landdwelling zombies, they are free-willed [\u2026]\nThe appearance of drowned ones matches their name: They look like human corpses that have been underwater for some time\u2014bloated and discolored flesh dripping with foul water, empty eye-sockets, tongue frequently protruding from between blackened lips. [\u2026] On land, drowned ones move slowly, with a clumsy shambling gait. In water, however, they can swim with frightening speed. [\u2026]\nThe water-logged condition of the creature's flesh means that fire and fire-based magic cause only half damage. Lightning, electrical, and coldbased attacks inflict double damage. Drowned ones are immune to sleep, charm, illusion, and other mind-altering spells. [\u2026]"}
{"id": "35581", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35581", "title": "Sea Zombie Lord", "text": "The Sea Zombie Lord is a &lt;a href=\"sea%20zombie\"&gt;sea zombie&lt;/a&gt; that still maintains at least some level of its human intelligence. More powerful than any ordinary sea zombie, it rules over a small court of other aquatic undead and eagerly seeks to kill any living creature that stumbles into the corner of the &lt;a href=\"Underwater%20City\"&gt;Underwater City&lt;/a&gt; that it has claimed for itself.\nLocations.\nA single sea zombie lord, accompanied by &lt;a href=\"Sea%20Zombie\"&gt;Sea Zombie minions&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Lacedon\"&gt;Greater Lacedon&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Lacedon\"&gt;Lacedon&lt;/a&gt;, is encountered in the charnel pit of the &lt;a href=\"Underwater%20City\"&gt;Underwater City&lt;/a&gt;. \nGameplay.\nWhen this creature detects any opponent in range, it and all the pit denizens will move toward it to attack. The Sea Lord will also croak out its one line of zombie dialogue. \nThough zombies are relatively sluggish in terms of movement speed, this one is under a permanent normal &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Haste effect&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe creature will attempt to engage in close quarters attacks with the closest party member it can detect. Its undroppable weapon is described on the &lt;a href=\"SAHZOM01.ITM\"&gt;Attack weapon&lt;/a&gt; page. If it connects upon a target, there is a 10% change of inflicting a &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;Disease&lt;/a&gt; effect, that can really hurt, inflicting 6 &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;Poison damage&lt;/a&gt; per second for one turn. That will eventually kill any party member who does not cure it before hit points are all gone. Additional hits are cumulative as well, so it is deadly indeed. Standard poison antidotes will suffice, or an appropriate Cleric spell. \nThe zombie can launch an innate ability (SPIN 666.spl) that is basically a ranged &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt; attack that bypasses &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; spell protections, and ignores spell school and secondary type defences. A save vs. Death negates, or two levels are drained. \nThe sea zombie lord's final throes manifest in death with a &lt;a href=\"Cloudkill\"&gt;Cloudkill&lt;/a&gt; application over the corpse. A fitting end for such a repulsive creature. Breath deeply the fragrant scent of victory. As any Cloudkill, it can be prematurely ended with &lt;a href=\"Zone%20of%20Sweet%20Air\"&gt;Zone of Sweet Air&lt;/a&gt;.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod adds an extra smarter AI script to the creature for improved tactical behavior and opponent vulnerability assessment. The creature may quaff its &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Extra%20Healing\"&gt;Potion of Extra Healing&lt;/a&gt; if hurt to a pre-set threshold of damage."}
