{"id": "47326", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47326", "title": "Sewage Golem", "text": "The Sewage Golem is found at rest in the storage room on the first floor of &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon%201st%20Floor\"&gt;Irenicus' Dungeon&lt;/a&gt;. It is in possession of the &lt;a href=\"Sewage%20Golem%20Key\"&gt;Sewage Golem Key&lt;/a&gt; which will open all three of the warded doors that lead to the sewage room. \nThe golem has limited \"programming\", and will not attack the party or become hostile. Likewise, it cannot be destroyed by hit point loss (which will never fall below 1). At this stage of the saga, the party is unlikely able to do anything to actually slay the big dumb automaton. So, don't waste too much time trying to figure out how to eke out some extra experience points.\nThe Sewage Room.\nThere are two different methods that can be carried out in order to obtain access to the sewage room.\nOnce the golem finishes performing its duties, it will return to the storage room."}
{"id": "39639", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=39639", "title": "Sewage Golem Key", "text": "The Sewage Golem Key is in the possession of the &lt;a href=\"Sewage%20Golem\"&gt;Sewage Golem&lt;/a&gt; which is located in the Storage room on the first floor of &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon%201st%20Floor\"&gt;Irenicus's Dungeon&lt;/a&gt;. It is required for opening any of the three doors that lead to the Sewage room.\nThe golem can be pick pocketed for the key by &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt; if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; isn't a thief."}
{"id": "20698", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20698", "title": "Sewer Cleaner", "text": "There are two Sewer Cleaners that can be found wandering about near the center point of the eastern section of the &lt;a href=\"Sewers%23AR0225\"&gt;Central Sewers&lt;/a&gt; that run underneath the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. They don't serve any purpose other than to provide cannon fodder for wayward lightning bolts, missed placed (location-wise) fireballs or other types of spells that may cause collateral damage when proper precautions aren't taken during spell casting."}
{"id": "8911", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8911", "title": "Sewer Key", "text": "The Sewer Key is found amongst the items carried by &lt;a href=\"Tazok\"&gt;Tazok&lt;/a&gt; and can be discovered as early as &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%202\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 2&lt;/a&gt;.\nLocation.\nIt is dropped by &lt;a href=\"Tazok\"&gt;Tazok&lt;/a&gt; at the end of the &lt;a href=\"Firkraag%27s%20Maze\"&gt;second level&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=\"Windspear%20Hills\"&gt;Windspear Hills&lt;/a&gt; dungeon. Precisely why it is located so far away from the door it serves to open is a mystery.\nGameplay.\nThe only clue as to what this key may open, is in the description for the key, and of course, it's title.\nA \"spoiler\" reveal button is below for readers who want to know the answer to this key. Don't read it if you desire to figure it out on your own as intended for a first time player.\nThe key will open the secret wall panel on the NE corridor of the &lt;a href=\"Sewers%20%28Temple%20District%29\"&gt;Sewers (Temple District)&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "47513", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47513", "title": "Sewerfolk", "text": "Sewerfolk are the followers of the mage turned olive slime &lt;a href=\"Schlumpsha%20the%20Sewer%20King\"&gt;Schlumpsha the Sewer King&lt;/a&gt;, all of whom are found in the &lt;a href=\"Sewers\"&gt;western sewers&lt;/a&gt; underneath the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. The sewerfolk have no dialogue and will obey the commands of their sewer king."}
{"id": "4314", "revid": "282480", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4314", "title": "Sewers", "text": "The stormwater grates on the ground in all areas of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; are not just decoration; they are passageways to three areas with connections to the whole of the city, even the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne\"&gt;Iron Throne&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Undercellar\"&gt;Undercellar&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Ducal%20Palace\"&gt;Ducal Palace&lt;/a&gt;. They make for a useful shortcut once you get used to all of the different exit points within them.\n&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20Sewers%20East\"&gt;East Sewers&lt;/a&gt;.\nOgre Mage and &lt;a href=\"Carrion%20Crawler\"&gt;Carrion Crawler&lt;/a&gt; pets at 1335, 1590. These creatures are the target of a quest &lt;a href=\"Missing%20Citizens\"&gt;Missing Citizens&lt;/a&gt; given by &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; member &lt;a href=\"Scar\"&gt;Scar&lt;/a&gt;. Loot includes: &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Bastard Sword +1&lt;/a&gt;\nor &lt;a href=\"Scimitar%20%2B1\"&gt;Scimitar +1&lt;/a&gt;\nand (&lt;a href=\"Sashenstar%27s%20Ruby%20Ring\"&gt;Sashenstar's&lt;/a&gt;) &lt;a href=\"Ruby%20Ring\"&gt;Ruby Ring&lt;/a&gt;; return the ring to &lt;a href=\"Scar\"&gt;Scar&lt;/a&gt;; do not sell it and be carefull when interacting with Farmer Brun in &lt;a href=\"Area%20North%20of%20the%20Friendly%20Arm\"&gt;Area North of the Friendly Arm&lt;/a&gt; because he will would take any Ruby Rings should the player return his son's body and offer him gold. Should the worst come to the worst, the quest can still be completed without the ring, but &lt;a href=\"Scar\"&gt;Scar&lt;/a&gt; will give a lesser reward. A possible solution is to find another ring; there is one in &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower\"&gt;Durlag's Tower&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "5976", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5976", "title": "Sewers (Slums District)", "text": "These Sewers are an underground series of tunnels in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Slums District&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe sewers beneath the Slums can be accessed from the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Slaver%20Stockade\"&gt;Slaver Stockade&lt;/a&gt;. The exit from the Copper Coronet enters into the northwest section of this area, the exit from the Slaver Stockade enters into the southeast section of this area.\nA second set of stairs in the northern part of the map leads to a &lt;a href=\"Myconid%20Area%20%28Slum%20Sewers%29\"&gt;Myconid Cave&lt;/a&gt;. \nMod content.\nMods:.\nInstall &lt;a href=\"The%20Minotaur%20and%20Lilacor\"&gt;The Minotaur and Lilacor&lt;/a&gt; Mod for additional content with the Myconid Area (Slum Sewers)."}
{"id": "13514", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13514", "title": "Sewers (Temple District)", "text": "The Athkatla Sewers are a series of tunnels below &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt;, where there are several iron grates on certain pathways which allow the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; to transition below. These are separate from the &lt;a href=\"Sewers%20%28Slums%20District%29\"&gt;Slums District sewers&lt;/a&gt;, and not connected.\nGameplay.\nThe sewers have an eight-spoke design with tunnels that cross in the center, where a &lt;a href=\"Rakshasa%20%28Sewers%29\"&gt;Rakshasa (Sewers)&lt;/a&gt; and his &lt;a href=\"Kobold\"&gt;Kobold&lt;/a&gt; allies interdict traffic.\nThis Raksasha is assisted by various ordinary &lt;a href=\"Kobold\"&gt;Kobold&lt;/a&gt;, a couple &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Commando\"&gt;Kobold Commando&lt;/a&gt; archers, a &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Captain\"&gt;Kobold Captain&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Shaman\"&gt;Kobold Shaman&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Witch%20Doctor\"&gt;Kobold Witch Doctor&lt;/a&gt;. That's three spell casting opponents the party may have to deal with if the party member enters their range of detection. Be careful not to become incapacitated or &lt;a href=\"Helpless\"&gt;Helpless&lt;/a&gt; from disabling magic.\nAt the south \"spoke\" is &lt;a href=\"Roger%20the%20Fence\"&gt;Roger the Fence&lt;/a&gt; who can relieve you of any \"hot\" merchandise you need to off-load (in other words, he buys stolen items). Roger also wants you to \"take care\" of a problem &lt;a href=\"Sea%20Troll\"&gt;Sea Troll&lt;/a&gt; a short distance away in the southwestern spoke. He'll offer a reward if the party accepts the job.\nUpon getting there, you might also trigger the spawning of yet another creature in that corner (e.g., &lt;a href=\"Otyugh\"&gt;Otyugh&lt;/a&gt;). If you have accepted the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless\"&gt;Investigate and Destroy the Cult of the Eyeless&lt;/a&gt; questline from any of the Temples, then you may see a teleportation animation and a &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt; and two &lt;a href=\"Gauth\"&gt;Gauth&lt;/a&gt;s appearing nearby the Otyugh spawning point. This an ambush. The appearance of the Beholder is PC level/experience dependent. If you are inexperienced fighting Beholders, you can avoid them by fleeing away from their visual range or going invisible/hidden.\nAt the north spoke is an adventuring group called &lt;a href=\"The%20Hatchetman%27s%20Party\"&gt;The Hatchetman's Party&lt;/a&gt; with whom you may either talk or fight. The party includes a &lt;a href=\"Zorl%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Gaius\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; and two fighters, &lt;a href=\"Tarnor%20the%20Hatchetman\"&gt;one of whom&lt;/a&gt; uses a returning &lt;a href=\"Hangard%27s%20Axe\"&gt;throwing axe&lt;/a&gt; to a good effect. The mage protects himself with &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; and then cast crowd-control spells like &lt;a href=\"Horror\"&gt;Horror&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;. Prepare for a tough fight.\nTo the northwest you find a &lt;a href=\"zombie\"&gt;zombie&lt;/a&gt; attacking a &lt;a href=\"Paladin\"&gt;Paladin&lt;/a&gt;; the latter is the potential companion, &lt;a href=\"Keldorn%20Firecam\"&gt;Keldon Firecam&lt;/a&gt;. Beyond is the entrance to &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels\"&gt;The Old Tunnels&lt;/a&gt;, only accessible if a priest has given you the quest to &lt;a href=\"Find%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Unseeing\"&gt;Find and Destroy the Cult of the Unseeing&lt;/a&gt;.\nTwo secret doors can also be found in the northern part of the map; one (northwest) leads to a &lt;a href=\"Mekrath%27s%20Laboratory\"&gt;hidden lair&lt;/a&gt;, the other (northeast) to the &lt;a href=\"Illithid%20Hideout%20in%20the%20Sewers\"&gt;secret area&lt;/a&gt;. The latter can't be accessed without a specific key only found from a specific opponent, in a specific place elsewhere in the saga. Find this key by adventuring and doing quests introduced to the party. The party can't get it now, and it isn't available from this map.\nThe northeastern and southeastern spokes are exits to the Temple District. \nMod content.\nPeople involved.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises most creatures in the sewers. Expect the Raksasha to deploy a battery of initial buffs when combat initiates (much different than the unmodified game version). Likewise, Tarnor's gang is improved with better AI and smarter spell use. If the party comes to blows with this bunch, expect a tougher fight by far.\nThe SCS \"Improved Beholder' Scripts and abilities will be a test as well if the party goes into beholder eye beam range. Expect being bathed in the beholder's &lt;a href=\"Anti-Magic%20Ray\"&gt;Anti-Magic Ray&lt;/a&gt;. On higher difficulty settings a party member could be exposed to petrification or disintegration effects. Forewarned is forearmed.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Quest%20Pack\"&gt;Quest Pack&lt;/a&gt; mod can install Rahul Kanakia\u2019s Potion Quest&lt;br&gt;\nOriginally created by Rahul Kanakia, this little-known gem makes a reappearance in Quest Pack. Edited by Ding0 and Compton, Potion Quest tells the tale of a man torn between work and family, and of the very real consequences of thirst for power. This quest begins in the southwest of the sewers beneath the Temple District.&lt;br&gt;\nPart of the &lt;a href=\"Unfinished%20Business%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%29\"&gt;Unfinished Business (Baldur's Gate II)&lt;/a&gt; mod and the &lt;a href=\"Pai%27Na%20and%20Spider%27s%20Bane\"&gt;Pai'Na and Spider's Bane&lt;/a&gt; questline plays out in the Sewers."}
{"id": "44389", "revid": "5305940", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44389", "title": "Sewers Exit", "text": "The Sewers Exit appears if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; was able to prove their innocence to &lt;a href=\"Schael%20Corwin\"&gt;Schael Corwin&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Abandoned%20Sewers%20%26amp%3B%20Caverns\"&gt;Abandoned Sewers &amp; Caverns&lt;/a&gt;. If Schael believed they were innocent, a cutscene will start with &lt;a href=\"Minsc\"&gt;Minsc&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Khalid\"&gt;Khalid&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Jaheira\"&gt;Jaheira&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt; \u2014 or as many of them can, if any are dead \u2014 reuniting with Gorion's Ward and progressing onward to &lt;a href=\"The%20Ambush\"&gt;The Ambush&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "23911", "revid": "3077225", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=23911", "title": "Sewers beneath Saradush", "text": "The Sewers beneath Saradush are an optional area that can be explored at the start of Chapter 8 in and its equivalent component in . Once the player has left &lt;a href=\"Saradush\"&gt;Saradush&lt;/a&gt;, they become inaccessible."}
{"id": "49788", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49788", "title": "Shade Lich", "text": "The Shade Lich is a powerful &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt; entombed in a crypt chamber located in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels\"&gt;The Old Tunnels&lt;/a&gt; which may be found as part of the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless\"&gt;Investigate and Destroy the Cult of the Eyeless&lt;/a&gt; questline. When first found, the crypt is temporarily inhabited by outcast cult members. Speak with &lt;a href=\"Sassar\"&gt;Sassar&lt;/a&gt; there. The Shade Lich is an integral part of the &lt;a href=\"Restore%20Kangaxx%27s%20body\"&gt;Restore Kangaxx's body&lt;/a&gt; questline. The Shade Lich guards body parts of &lt;a href=\"Kangaxx\"&gt;Kangaxx&lt;/a&gt;, which are stored within the sarcophagus. If a player interacts with the sarcophagus and attempts to open it, the Shade Lich will rise from the Crypt Floor, and regardless of anything the party may say - eventually turn hostile. It will attempt to destroy you, the would-be Crypt robbers. The name Shade Lich is derived by the fact that no name is mentioned directly as to this creature's actual name, however the game combat screen identifies it as the \"Shade Lich\".\nShade Lich Abilities.\nThis creature receives passive \"always on\" and non dispellable powers from items equipped in certain slots. The items are not droppable or stealable.\nThese items are:\nSee the infoBox for a breakdown of immunities and special powers.\nMod content.\nInstallation of &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod will improve the Shade Lich's AI noticeably over the basic and unmodified game versions of the creature. If the SCS \"Smarter Mages\" component is also installed, this Lich will be even more formidable, in that it will utilize triggers, sequencers and contingency abilities. This component also works with the game difficulty settings, and this could mean that a Lich will also have access, and use, Mage &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; powers. \nSCS makes the Shade Lich a Level 30 Necromancer (it could also be an enchanter, conjurer or invoker - depends on the installation variable). Many different memorized spells are assigned and most are different than the unmodded Lich shown in the main info box. Examples include (not all are listed): &lt;a href=\"Shield\"&gt;Shield&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spook\"&gt;Spook&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Horror\"&gt;Horror&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ray%20of%20Enfeeblement\"&gt;Ray of Enfeeblement&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20from%20Fire\"&gt;Protection from Fire&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Skull%20Trap\"&gt;Skull Trap&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Thrust\"&gt;Spell Thrust&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Contagion\"&gt;Contagion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Malison\"&gt;Greater Malison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cloudkill\"&gt;Cloudkill&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20from%20Acid\"&gt;Protection from Acid&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Animate%20Dead\"&gt;Animate Dead&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Disintegrate\"&gt;Disintegrate&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magic%20Energy\"&gt;Protection From Magic Energy&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death\"&gt;Finger of Death&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Khelben%27s%20Warding%20Whip\"&gt;Khelben's Warding Whip&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Abi-Dalzim%27s%20Horrid%20Wilting\"&gt;Abi-Dalzim's Horrid Wilting&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Symbol, Death (wizard)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Imprisonment\"&gt;Imprisonment&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Energy%20Drain\"&gt;Energy Drain&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Trap\"&gt;Spell Trap&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spellstrike\"&gt;Spellstrike&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Time%20Stop\"&gt;Time Stop&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn addition, Mage HLA's are available, including &lt;a href=\"Comet\"&gt;Comet&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dragon%27s%20Breath%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Dragon's Breath (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Energy%20Blades%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Energy Blades (wizard)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Alacrity\"&gt;Improved Alacrity&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Dark%20Planetar\"&gt;Summon Dark Planetar&lt;/a&gt;. \nAll SCS liches can see invisible creatures, and this cannot be blocked or dispelled. \nThis creature will employ a \"Fear Aura\" ability, an innate power with a fairly large area of effect. A saving throw with a penalty negates, but it is unaffected by spell level protections and magic resistance. It causes a &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;Panic&lt;/a&gt; effect and lasts a turn.\nIf the SCS \"More Consistent Breach\" component is installed, a level 5 &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; Spell can target a Lich, which it cannot in an unmodified game. However, SCS changes Breach to be blocked by all of the Spell Protection options such as Spell Shield, Spell Deflection, Spell Turning and Spell Trap.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod will replace the Lich's memorized spells with the SR versions. It leaves the innate abilities alone."}
{"id": "26677", "revid": "285357", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26677", "title": "Shade Lord", "text": "The Shade Lord is the final villain in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20Ruins\"&gt;Temple Ruins&lt;/a&gt; in \"\".\nHe can be reached only by going through the entire &lt;a href=\"Ruined%20Temple\"&gt;temple&lt;/a&gt;, collecting several relics and finally fighting or sneaking past his allied Shadow Dragon &lt;a href=\"Thaxll%27ssillyia\"&gt;Thaxll'ssillyia&lt;/a&gt;. \nFacing the Shade Lord.\nWhen confronted, the Shade Lord will try to claim &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; as his next host, assisted by the &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Patrick\"&gt;Shadow Patrick&lt;/a&gt;, as well as other shadows that he can call upon to fight for him. There is no choice other than to face the Shade Lord when he is encountered. If &lt;a href=\"Mazzy%20Fentan\"&gt;Mazzy Fentan&lt;/a&gt; is a party companion, there will be additional dialogue and reply options.\nGameplay.\nAfter dialogue, the Shade Lord, &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Patrick\"&gt;Shadow Patrick&lt;/a&gt;, two &lt;a href=\"Shadow\"&gt;Shadow&lt;/a&gt; creatures and the &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Altar\"&gt;Shadow Altar&lt;/a&gt; spring into hostile action. Note that the Shade Lord has access to innate, arcane and divine spells - and they are not limited by memory and aren't exhausted. The script determines when and what spell to attempt based on conditions and timed intervals.\nThe Shade Lord will usually attack the nearest opponent with a \"Shadow Drain\" innate spell attack (SPIN878). A Gaze projectile travels to the target, and it bypasses magic resistance and spell protections. Save vs. Breath negates. Fail and &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt; effect value of 2 experience levels, as well as 1 round of &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt;, which has no saving throw. The &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt; could deflect it if the targeted member has that equipped.\nIf Mazzy is detected by the Shade Lord, she will be the target of a &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Stun\"&gt;Symbol, Stun&lt;/a&gt; spell. If any spell casting class (mage, priest, bard or druid and sub classes) are detected, then a &lt;a href=\"Silence%2C%2015%27%20Radius\"&gt;Silence, 15' Radius&lt;/a&gt; will be cast. Also, if any spell casting class is detected a &lt;a href=\"Spellstrike\"&gt;Spellstrike&lt;/a&gt; can be launched.\nIf the Shade lord is hit by crushing damage or its Hit points fall to 25% of maximum a contingency will instantly apply &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Blade%20Barrier\"&gt;Blade Barrier&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis creature can also attempt &lt;a href=\"Chromatic%20Orb\"&gt;Chromatic Orb&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Finger of Death (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; spell casts at detected enemies.\nAbsent the spell casting, the lord will also engage in melee attacks with its touch attack weapon. it has a 1\u00a0ft range with 0 speed, dealing 3d4+9 &lt;a href=\"piercing%20damage\"&gt;piercing damage&lt;/a&gt; with a &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; of 5, including the &lt;a href=\"strength\"&gt;strength&lt;/a&gt; bonus. This \"weapon\" is treated as having an &lt;a href=\"Enchanted%20item\"&gt;enchantment&lt;/a&gt; of +1 in the and of +4 in the \"\".\nMod Content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod, and the Tactical Challenges for BG2 component upgrades the Shade Lord, mostly by giving him additional magical powers (though his hit points are also increased). Unlike most components, this one doesn't make any particular effort to stick with the vanilla game or with anything from source material: like the Wolf of Ulcaster, the Shade Lord has his own unique abilities. The Shade Lord casts all spell types at caster level 20. It's saving throws are adjusted slightly in favor of bonuses, especially save vs spell. The creature has 100% cold resistance and is immune to instant death effects like &lt;a href=\"Slay\"&gt;Slay&lt;/a&gt;.\nAt the beginning of the battle the Shade Lord instantly applies the following protective buffs (can't be interrupted): &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;.\nA few tics later an SCS only unique innate spell called \"Darkling Aura\" is force cast over itself, which generates a &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt; effect against any opponents in the area of effect. This Necromancy and Disabling type ability is unaffected by magic resistance, spell protections and has no saving throw. It will drain 1 experience level that has a temporary duration of 1 turn. &lt;a href=\"Negative%20Plane%20Protection\"&gt;Negative Plane Protection&lt;/a&gt; or equivalent will prevent the effect.\nNext, the lord will attempt to cast &lt;a href=\"Black%20Blade%20of%20Disaster\"&gt;Black Blade of Disaster&lt;/a&gt;, which has a long casting time, and can be potentially interrupted. If the Black Blade is successful, the creature will alternate weapon attacks and spell casting at the closest opponent in melee range. \nA &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Blind\"&gt;Power Word, Blind&lt;/a&gt; will be directed at the closest opponent within a few rounds of the battle going on.\nIf no one closes, it will continue to cast spells including &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death\"&gt;Finger of Death&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Chromatic%20Orb\"&gt;Chromatic Orb&lt;/a&gt; unless the only target it can detect is protected against spells or has the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt; equipped. Additionally, the lord can continue to apply the \"Darkling Aura\" about every three rounds.\nThe creature will most likely cast &lt;a href=\"Blade%20Barrier\"&gt;Blade Barrier&lt;/a&gt; at some point in the battle after five rounds, if able and still functioning. "}
{"id": "11309", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11309", "title": "Shade Wolf", "text": "Shade Wolves are similar to &lt;a href=\"Vampiric%20Wolf\"&gt;vampiric wolves&lt;/a&gt;. They are immune to normal weapons and must be fought with spells or magical weapons. Presumably, they can be turned by &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;s. They do 1d8 piercing damage with each successful attack."}
{"id": "55998", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=55998", "title": "Shades of the Sword Coast", "text": "Shades of the Sword Coast is a mod for \"\" and &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition%20Trilogy\"&gt;EET&lt;/a&gt; that adds many small-to-medium quests all over the game world.\nOverview.\nThe quests tend to center around the themes of undeath, memories, and the ethereal. Several add beautiful new maps \u2013 mostly new side areas of existing areas, such as caves.\nExternal links.\n\"(For the mod's main website/forum/download page, see the infobox above.)\""}
{"id": "55997", "revid": "282029", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=55997", "title": "Shades of the Sword Coast walkthrough", "text": "This is a walkthrough for the quest content added by the \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;BG1&lt;/a&gt;\" mod \"&lt;a href=\"Shades%20of%20the%20Sword%20Coast\"&gt;Shades of the Sword Coast&lt;/a&gt;\".\nThe quests are independent of each other, and can be done in any order, unless otherwise specified.\nThis walkthrough groups the quests by the chapter or expansion they can first be started in.\nChapter 1 to 3.\nRandom encounters.\nThe mod adds the following &lt;a href=\"Random_Encounter_%28BG%29\"&gt;random encounters&lt;/a&gt; that can pop up when you travel between worldmap areas."}
{"id": "24177", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24177", "title": "Shadow", "text": "A Shadow is an &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; creature of darkness and the negative plane or the Domains of Dread. They are malign creatures that hate the living and the light.\nGameplay.\nThese creatures relentlessly follow their prey, seeking to attack them with their partially substantial and flexible tendril-like shadow claws.\nEach melee blow from a Shadow against any creature will temporarily drain an &lt;a href=\"Ability%20Scores\"&gt;Attribute&lt;/a&gt; point of &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt;. Multiple hits are additive and could lead to death by lowering strength to zero.\nThese creatures are not fully tangible on the prime plane, so are less hardy than many living beings. They are vulnerable to physical attacks, fire, and some magics.\nOnly an enchanted or &lt;a href=\"Magical%20item\"&gt;Magical Weapon&lt;/a&gt; will be able to strike these creatures.\nThey are however immune to a number of elemental damage types and status effects, as itemized in the InfoBox."}
{"id": "37617", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37617", "title": "Shadow Ally", "text": ""}
{"id": "9053", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9053", "title": "Thardek", "text": "Thardek is the light weapons in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\".\nHe turns out to be a traitor to his kind: he gave &lt;a href=\"Baeloth%20Barrityl\"&gt;Baeloth&lt;/a&gt; information about the &lt;a href=\"duergar\"&gt;duergar&lt;/a&gt; warrens when the &lt;a href=\"drow\"&gt;drow&lt;/a&gt; arrived to take slaves.\nThardek (store).\nWhile his direct market stall neighbor &lt;a href=\"Magda\"&gt;Magda&lt;/a&gt; has specialized in heavier , Thardek's \"light\" weapons are mostly those a &lt;a href=\"thief\"&gt;thief&lt;/a&gt;, among other &lt;a href=\"classes\"&gt;classes&lt;/a&gt;, would be able to use in melee combat. His palette increases with the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt;'s progress throughout the various \"Tiers\" of the arena battles. &lt;a href=\"Item\"&gt;Item&lt;/a&gt;s from earlier Tiers will be still available later and previously purchased ones restocked.\nHe sells at 145% of an item's base value and buys far more than only weapons for 30% item value, at a &lt;a href=\"depreciation%20rate\"&gt;depreciation rate&lt;/a&gt; of 5. Prices might be further modified through high &lt;a href=\"charisma\"&gt;charisma&lt;/a&gt; or an other-than-average &lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt;.\nIt is not possible to steal from his store."}
{"id": "30771", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30771", "title": "Thassk's Journal", "text": ""}
{"id": "7465", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7465", "title": "Thaxll'ssillyia", "text": "Thaxll'ssillyia is a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20dragons\"&gt;shadow dragon&lt;/a&gt; serving the &lt;a href=\"Shade%20Lord\"&gt;Shade Lord&lt;/a&gt;. He can be found in the penultimate room of the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20Ruins\"&gt;ruined temple&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Amaunator\"&gt;Amaunator&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nUpon descending the staircase from the level above, your party will enter a cathedral-like open area. During daylight hours, dim light penetrates the dark interior from windows higher up on the walls. The stink of rotting flesh and decay assails your nostrils. A dormant hulking beast is visible within, with great folded leathery wings astride its armored body. There are barely discernable signs of life, such as rhythmic deep breathing. Its eyes appear slitted and half-closed. The great tail from the beast is curled protectively around a pile of bones, golden coins and other valuables. Perhaps this black and grey scaled dragon is in some kind of slumber? If you have the &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Dragon%20Wardstone\"&gt;Shadow Dragon Wardstone&lt;/a&gt; in your possession, the beast doesn't react to your presence. \nThe wardstone will prevent the dragon from being aware of your existence, until some kind of overt action on your part takes place - including speaking to or touching the dragon. Otherwise, it remains still. You do not need to arouse the dragon for any quest completion purpose, and you can safely ignore it. If you wish to claim its treasure hoard or destroy the fell beast then you may do so by announcing yourself by speaking to it, or just attack it with a huge tactical advantage. It is up to you.\nIf you decide to take on the dragon, get its attention by speaking with it, or attacking it in some manner. It will spring to action with a roar of dialogue in the common tongue, and then engage in battle (assuming it survived some kind of initial surprise attack or spell barrage). \nThe dragon has several innate abilities and innate spells it can muster to defend itself and harm you. These abilities and spells can't be interrupted or disrupted by damage. Expect the beast to immediately protect itself with &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; (10 skins) and then launch a level 23 &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt; upon the closest enemy. Anyone in melee range may also be attacked by its &lt;a href=\"DRAGBLAW.ITM\"&gt;piercing claws&lt;/a&gt;. It can get at least 3 strikes per round at a target.\nShortly thereafter, the dragon will radiate an aura of &lt;a href=\"Dragon%20Fear\"&gt;Dragon Fear&lt;/a&gt; in a circle around itself. Those within a certain distance and not immune to &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;Panic&lt;/a&gt; effects must make a saving throw to negate this, with a penalty, or they will flee and be uncontrollable (possibly involuntarily wetting their codpiece). \nThis is followed by a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Dragon%20Breath\"&gt;Shadow Dragon Breath&lt;/a&gt; blast upon an opponent closest to the dragon, and then several seconds later, a &lt;a href=\"Wing%20Buffet\"&gt;Wing Buffet&lt;/a&gt;. These innate abilities will continue to periodically be unleashed every few rounds (three) - Dragon Fear aura, breath attack and Wing buffet. In between these, the dragon will continue to try and damage the nearest opponent with claw attacks. \nIf the battle rages for a few more rounds, and the beast is still functional, it will begin to auto-cast some innate spells, such as &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Malison\"&gt;Greater Malison&lt;/a&gt; and 35% chance of a &lt;a href=\"Chromatic%20Orb\"&gt;Chromatic Orb&lt;/a&gt;. Additionally, if the dragon's melee opponent is protected so that the creature's melee attack is \"weapon ineffective\", it may reciprocate and protect itself with &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt;. All of the dragon's innate spells are inexhaustible, and the only limitation is the time delay between their uses. In other words, the beast will not \"run out\" of spells or innate abilities.\nThaxll'ssillyia has no innate weapon immunities, meaning even normal, unenchanted weapons can hurt it. Switching to normal weapons is one way to hurt it when it casts &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt;. The player still has to negate its &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; can negate both.\nStrategy.\nThis might be the first dragon faced by the party in the saga. It is one of the more dangerous enemies in the early SoA game, especially if the party decides to face it as soon as &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%202\"&gt;Chapter II&lt;/a&gt;. As usual, proper preparation is the key to winning this battle with minimal strain.\nParty members that will be close to the dragon, especially in melee range - will need protection from &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt;. Perhaps a party cleric could cast &lt;a href=\"Negative%20Plane%20Protection\"&gt;Negative Plane Protection&lt;/a&gt;. If the party has an item that provided this protection such as the &lt;a href=\"Amulet%20of%20Power\"&gt;Amulet of Power&lt;/a&gt;, that would be optimal. A Berserker or Barbarian kit ability can provide protection for a limited time. Unprotected party members in range to the dragon are at high risk. \nProtection from fear effects, like &lt;a href=\"Panic\"&gt;Panic&lt;/a&gt; would be prudent for those close by. A &lt;a href=\"Resist%20Fear\"&gt;Resist Fear&lt;/a&gt; spell will do the trick. If that isn't available, then boosting saving throws vs. spell would be another method to mitigate the chances of being frightened and uncontrollable.\nStoneskin would be useful to be able to engage in melee with the dragon, as it hits often and for a considerable quantity of damage. A means to heal the damage is also needed, if the skins are consumed. &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; is also a good defense for a limited time. Expect to be damaged while in melee, and the longer it goes on, the more likely healing will required.\nBe prepared for being knocked backwards by the Wing buffeting force. It is hard to resist, especially in unmodded games and early in the saga. You should have a plan for what to do if a single or multiple party members are blown backwards at once. If the dragon has no one to occupy its attention close by, it may advance to another party member (that may be unsuited to go toe to claw with a dragon).\nThe use of summoned creatures may be a great help. Let those creatures occupy the beast, while the party cast spells or fires missiles from a distance.\nSpread out your party so that area of effect spells and attacks can't get multiple members in each use. Keep the dragon busy with at least one party member or summoned creature and overwhelm it with ranged attacks and spells.\nA party member could polymorph into a &lt;a href=\"Mustard%20Jelly\"&gt;Mustard Jelly&lt;/a&gt; via spell or using the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20the%20Sewers\"&gt;Cloak of the Sewers&lt;/a&gt;. The form is invulnerable to the dragon's claw attacks. That may be a viable option to increase staying power and get close to the dragon while others deal the damage. If soloing, then this would be good method to eventually defeat the beast. \nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; revises Thaxll'ssillyia in many ways. Especially if you install the \"Smarter Dragons\" component (which is responsive to the game difficulty selection). His SCS AI improves targeting and recognition of opponent's protections, which means he will fight smarter and not waste attacks on someone he cannot hit or damage. It will also influence his tactical options and attack methods. First, some mention of the dragon's stats and abilities. In most cases, all of the unmodded ones are still applicable:\nImmunities in addition to the unmodded dragon version:\nAs stated in the article above, Thaxll'ssillyia has access to several innate Dragon abilities. They are uninterruptible. A little bit more on what SCS does with the following:\nSpells: Thaxll'ssillyia is scripted to use the following spells, as determined by the AI's need, and your party's protections: &lt;a href=\"Chromatic%20Orb\"&gt;Chromatic Orb&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Malison\"&gt;Greater Malison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;. \nSCS looks for the party preparing for battle, simulating that Thaxll'ssillyia would be alerted of an imminent hostile action. Any trap setting, creature or demon summoning or certain spells will possibly trigger a hostile reaction. I won't spoil the spells it looks for, but it includes many of the favorite party-wide buffs from wizards and clerics such as Haste and Draw upon Holy Might, Protection from Fire and others. You just can't buff with certain spells in the presence of the dragon without triggering a response. Forget setting a trap near the dragon or within visual range. If you summon an elemental, or some cannon fodder from the wand of summoning of any kind, he will become hostile. Buffing and summoning must occur out of sight from the dragon. If a summoned creature moves into visual range that will also trigger a hostile reaction.\nOne warning for a party facing the dragon. SCS AI can recognize members that are protected from level drain. It sees Blackguards, Undead Hunter, Enrage ability, Negative Plane Protection, and similar. It will try and aim a breath weapon attack at someone who has no level drain protection. Keep those individuals out of the dragon's sight range (which is about 30 feet, at least as good as a party member.) If a breath attack is launched at a member, they may try to run away as the projectile heads toward them and out run it, but that is difficult (but not impossible). A good length of distance is needed for that tactic to work, and Haste or Speed boots.\nOn \"Insane\" difficulty, the dragon has better saving throws (probably will not fail any, unless a Greater Malison is used, and then, rarely). Regains use of Shadow Dragon Breath quicker than the unmodded game. Could potentially by percentage, have a 50% chance each round to blast with it. \nFor the greatest challenge, speak with the dragon in order to hear his threats and boasts, and only then engage in combat. Do not attack unprovoked with the wardstone in your inventory for a fairer battle experience. \nWith the installation of the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod, some of the dragon's arcane memorized spells will be the SR version. The innate abilities mostly are not revised except for the dragon breath. With SCS or SR, the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt; bug behavior is fixed, so the spell works as it should. It no longer interacts at all with the Dragon's breath attack. In the unmodded game the Spell Shield bug trivializes the dragon's breath weapon, which is most probably an unintended coding omission.\nAchievements.\nShadow Dragon Slayer.\nSlew the shadow dragon, Thaxll'ssillyia."}
{"id": "7388", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7388", "title": "Thay", "text": "Thay is magocracy in eastern &lt;a href=\"Faer%C3%BBn\"&gt;Faer\u00fbn&lt;/a&gt; bordered to the north by &lt;a href=\"Rashemen\"&gt;Rashemen&lt;/a&gt;. Thay is ruled by council of Zulkirs, eight powerful &lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;Specialist Mage&lt;/a&gt;s representing each School of Magic. The &lt;a href=\"Red%20Wizards%20of%20Thay\"&gt;Red Wizards of Thay&lt;/a&gt;, a powerful organization of mages serves as the ruling class of noblemen in Thayan society and appoints the Zulkirs. Thay is infamous for legalizing slavery.\nThay is often at war with its neighbours of Rashemen, taking conquered Rashemi people as slaves. This is the reason for the strong hatred between the two nations.\n&lt;a href=\"Edwin%20Odesseiron\"&gt;Edwin Odesseiron&lt;/a&gt; hails from Thay and it is strongly implied that he is a member of the Red Wizards. His plan to kill &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt; reflects the Thayan-Rashemi relations."}
